type: page
title: Food
---

Food is at the heart of your colony's daily life. Raw crops harvested by your {% worker name="farmer" plural=true /%} are processed into meals by the {% worker name="chef" /%} at the {% building name="kitchen" /%}, then cooked and served to hungry citizens by the {% worker name="cook" /%} at the {% building name="cook" /%}. The {% worker name="baker" /%} at the {% building name="baker" /%} rounds out the food supply with baked goods.

While citizens can eat vanilla food items, Minecolonies food is organized into tiers that determine how well it satisfies your citizens. Using vanilla food carries a penalty, so it is worth investing in a proper food production chain to keep your colony running at its best.

Each crop can only be found and grown in its required biome, one of four categories: cold, temperate, humid, or dry. This means your colony's location determines which crops are available to you. Some higher-tier dishes require ingredients from multiple biomes, so obtaining them will require trading with other colonies.

## Hunger and Saturation

Each citizen has a saturation bar, visible in their GUI, that works similarly to the player's hunger bar. Saturation drains as citizens work and again when they go to sleep, with higher-level workers losing more saturation each night. When it runs low, citizens will make their way to the {% building name="cook" /%} to be fed by the {% worker name="cook" /%}. If no {% building name="cook" /%} is available, they will request one or ask you to provide food manually.

A well-fed citizen heals faster and levels more effectively. If saturation reaches 0, the citizen will stop working, stop leveling, gain the slowness effect, and regularly request food in chat. Below a certain saturation level they also stop healing entirely, while a fully saturated citizen heals at double speed.

Citizens will demand higher levels of food based on their workplace level. **They will not eat food that doesn't meet (or exceed) their requirements.**

For more details on how saturation affects citizen happiness, see the [Happiness](/wiki/needs/happiness) page.

